Critical bug: The array coalescing loop has incorrect logic when performing in-place shifts. When `drop` is true and `i < num - 1`, the element at `i+1` is moved to `i`, but then the loop increments `i`, causing the newly moved element at `i` to be skipped without processing. This means some callbacks may not be properly checked for redundancy.

Example: If callbacks[0] should be dropped, callbacks[1] is moved to callbacks[0]. Then `i` becomes 1, so callbacks[0] (which was originally callbacks[1]) is never checked.

Suggestion: Use a separate index for writing or iterate backwards when removing elements.

```suggestion
    // Coalesce redundant updates and only keep the newest one.
    bool drop = false;
    int write_idx = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < mpctx->num_option_callbacks; i++) {
        if (flags && flags == mpctx->option_callbacks[i].flags)
            drop = true;
        if (mpctx->option_callbacks[i].co && opt_ptr == mpctx->option_callbacks[i].co->data)
            drop = true;
        if (!drop) {
            if (write_idx != i)
                mpctx->option_callbacks[write_idx] = mpctx->option_callbacks[i];
            write_idx++;
        }
    }
    mpctx->num_option_callbacks = write_idx;
```

